{
  "What is speciation?": "",
  "The extinction of a species": "",
  "The formation of new species from an ancestral population": "",
  "The adaptation of a species to a new environment": "",
  "The migration of a species to a new location": "",
  "Speciation is the evolutionary process by which populations diverge and develop reproductive isolation, eventually forming distinct species that can no longer interbreed to produce fertile offspring.": "",
  "Allopatric speciation occurs when populations are separated by:": "",
  "A physical geographic barrier": "",
  "Different mating seasons": "",
  "Behavioral differences": "",
  "Chromosomal mutations": "",
  "Allopatric speciation occurs when a geographic barrier (mountain range, river, ocean) physically separates populations, preventing gene flow and allowing independent evolution to produce reproductive isolation.": "",
  "Which of the following is a prezygotic reproductive barrier?": "",
  "Hybrid sterility": "",
  "Temporal isolation due to different breeding seasons": "",
  "Hybrid inviability": "",
  "Reduced fitness of hybrid offspring": "",
  "Temporal isolation is a prezygotic barrier that prevents mating because species breed at different times (different seasons, times of day, or years). Prezygotic barriers prevent the formation of hybrid zygotes.": "",
  "Sympatric speciation differs from allopatric speciation because it occurs:": "",
  "Without geographic separation of populations": "",
  "Only in aquatic environments": "",
  "Over much longer time periods than allopatric speciation": "",
  "Only through natural selection": "",
  "Sympatric speciation occurs within the same geographic area without a physical barrier. It can result from polyploidy (especially in plants), habitat differentiation, or disruptive selection that creates reproductive isolation.": "",
  "Polyploidy is most commonly associated with speciation in:": "",
  "Mammals": "",
  "Plants": "",
  "Bacteria": "",
  "Insects": "",
  "Polyploidy (having more than two complete sets of chromosomes) is a major mechanism of sympatric speciation in plants. Many crop species are polyploid. It is rare in animals because it disrupts sex determination.": "",
  "The biological species concept defines a species as a group of organisms that:": "",
  "Live in the same geographic area": "",
  "Can interbreed and produce viable, fertile offspring": "",
  "Look physically identical": "",
  "Share the same number of chromosomes": "",
  "The biological species concept, proposed by Ernst Mayr, defines species as populations that can interbreed in nature to produce viable, fertile offspring and are reproductively isolated from other such groups.": "",
  "Mass extinctions are significant in macroevolution because they:": "",
  "Have no long-term effect on evolution": "",
  "Open ecological niches that surviving lineages can diversify into through adaptive radiation": "",
  "Only affect organisms in the ocean": "",
  "Permanently reduce biodiversity with no recovery": "",
  "Mass extinctions eliminate many species and open ecological niches. Surviving lineages often undergo adaptive radiation to fill these vacant niches, dramatically reshaping the diversity of life. For example, mammals radiated after the dinosaur extinction.": "",
  "A mule is the offspring of a horse and a donkey. The mule is sterile. This is an example of which postzygotic barrier?": "",
  "Mechanical isolation": "",
  "Temporal isolation": "",
  "Gametic isolation": "",
  "Hybrid sterility is a postzygotic barrier where the hybrid offspring is viable but unable to reproduce. Mules are sterile because horses and donkeys have different chromosome numbers, preventing proper meiosis.": "",
  "The punctuated equilibrium model proposes that:": "",
  "Species remain largely unchanged for long periods, with rapid bursts of change associated with speciation events": "",
  "Extinction never occurs in evolution": "",
  "Evolution occurs at a constant, gradual rate": "",
  "All evolution occurs through genetic drift": "",
  "Punctuated equilibrium, proposed by Gould and Eldredge, suggests that species experience long periods of stasis with little change, interrupted by brief episodes of rapid evolutionary change, typically associated with speciation events.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of a prezygotic barrier called mechanical isolation?": "",
  "Two species use different courtship songs": "",
  "Hybrid offspring fail to develop properly": "",
  "Two species have incompatible reproductive structures that prevent mating": "",
  "Two species breed at different times of year": "",
  "Mechanical isolation occurs when differences in the size or shape of reproductive organs prevent successful mating between species. This is a prezygotic barrier because it prevents the formation of a zygote.": "",
  "What does 'reproductive isolation' mean?": "",
  "The inability of organisms within a species to reproduce": "",
  "Barriers that prevent members of different species from interbreeding or producing fertile offspring": "",
  "The process by which organisms reproduce asexually": "",
  "The physical separation of organisms from their mates": "",
  "Reproductive isolation encompasses all biological barriers that prevent members of different species from interbreeding or producing viable, fertile offspring. These barriers maintain species as distinct evolutionary lineages.": "",
  "What does 'allopatric speciation' mean?": "",
  "Speciation that occurs within the same geographic area": "",
  "Speciation caused exclusively by polyploidy": "",
  "The process by which two species merge into one": "",
  "Speciation that occurs when a population is split by a geographic barrier, preventing gene flow and allowing independent evolution": "",
  "Allopatric speciation (allo = other, patric = homeland) occurs when populations are geographically separated. Without gene flow, the isolated populations independently accumulate genetic differences that eventually lead to reproductive isolation.": "",
  "What is 'sympatric speciation'?": "",
  "Speciation that requires millions of years": "",
  "Speciation caused only by natural selection": "",
  "Speciation that occurs within the same geographic area without physical separation of populations": "",
  "The extinction of one species replaced by another": "",
  "Sympatric speciation (sym = same, patric = homeland) occurs without geographic isolation. It can result from polyploidy, habitat differentiation within the same area, or sexual selection leading to assortative mating.": "",
  "What does 'polyploidy' mean?": "",
  "Having more than two complete sets of chromosomes in a cell": "",
  "Having exactly two sets of chromosomes": "",
  "Having fewer chromosomes than normal": "",
  "Having one set of chromosomes": "",
  "Polyploidy is the condition of having more than two complete sets of chromosomes (e.g., triploid = 3n, tetraploid = 4n). It is a major mechanism of instant speciation in plants because polyploid individuals are often reproductively isolated from their diploid parents.": "",
  "What does 'adaptive radiation' mean?": "",
  "The spread of one species across many continents": "",
  "The gradual extinction of many species in a lineage": "",
  "The rapid diversification of a single ancestral lineage into many species adapted to different ecological niches": "",
  "The evolution of radiation resistance in organisms": "",
  "Adaptive radiation is the rapid evolutionary diversification of a single ancestral species into many descendant species, each filling different ecological niches. It typically occurs after mass extinctions or colonization of new habitats with open niches.": "",
  "What is 'gradualism' in evolutionary biology?": "",
  "The idea that evolution occurs through slow, steady accumulation of small changes over long periods": "",
  "The gradual decrease in population size leading to extinction": "",
  "The process of grading organisms by their fitness": "",
  "The sudden appearance of new species without transitional forms": "",
  "Gradualism proposes that evolutionary change occurs through the slow, continuous accumulation of small modifications over many generations. Darwin favored this view, and it contrasts with the punctuated equilibrium model.": "",
  "What does 'punctuated equilibrium' mean?": "",
  "A model stating that evolution always occurs at a constant rate": "",
  "A model of evolution proposing long periods of little change (stasis) interrupted by brief periods of rapid speciation": "",
  "The extinction of organisms due to sudden environmental changes": "",
  "The process by which organisms reach a stable equilibrium with their environment": "",
  "Punctuated equilibrium, proposed by Gould and Eldredge, suggests species are generally stable (in equilibrium) for most of their existence, with evolutionary change concentrated in relatively brief episodes associated with speciation events.": "",
  "What is a 'prezygotic barrier'?": "",
  "A mutation that prevents cell division": "",
  "A mechanism that prevents hybrid offspring from surviving": "",
  "A geographic barrier that separates populations": "",
  "A reproductive barrier that prevents the formation of a zygote by impeding mating or fertilization between species": "",
  "Prezygotic barriers act before fertilization to prevent hybrid zygote formation. They include habitat isolation, temporal isolation, behavioral isolation, mechanical isolation, and gametic isolation.": "",
  "What is a 'postzygotic barrier'?": "",
  "A physical barrier that separates two populations": "",
  "A barrier that prevents organisms from migrating to new habitats": "",
  "A barrier that prevents DNA replication": "",
  "A reproductive barrier that acts after fertilization, reducing the viability or fertility of hybrid offspring": "",
  "Postzygotic barriers act after a hybrid zygote forms. They include hybrid inviability (hybrid fails to develop), hybrid sterility (hybrid is infertile), and hybrid breakdown (F2 or later generations have reduced fitness).": "",
  "What does 'mass extinction' mean?": "",
  "A dramatic, widespread event in which a large proportion of all species on Earth go extinct in a geologically short period": "",
  "The normal background rate of species extinction": "",
  "The extinction of a single species due to competition": "",
  "The local disappearance of a population from one habitat": "",
  "A mass extinction is a global event where a significant proportion of species go extinct in a relatively short geological time span. Five major mass extinctions are recognized in Earth's history, each followed by periods of adaptive radiation.": "",
  "The Grand Canyon has separated two populations of squirrels for millions of years. The Kaibab squirrel on the North Rim has a white tail, while the Abert's squirrel on the South Rim has a gray tail. They can no longer interbreed successfully. What type of speciation does this illustrate?": "",
  "Artificial selection by humans living near the canyon": "",
  "Allopatric speciation, where the geographic barrier of the canyon prevented gene flow and allowed independent evolution": "",
  "Sympatric speciation through habitat differentiation": "",
  "Parapatric speciation along the edge of the canyon": "",
  "This is a classic example of allopatric speciation. The Grand Canyon physically separated the squirrel populations, preventing gene flow. Over millions of years, independent evolution led to distinct morphological and genetic differences and reproductive isolation.": "",
  "A plant species has 2n = 14 chromosomes. After an error in meiosis, a tetraploid individual (4n = 28) is produced. This individual can self-fertilize and produce fertile tetraploid offspring, but cannot produce fertile offspring with the original diploid species. What has occurred?": "",
  "Sympatric speciation through autopolyploidy, creating instant reproductive isolation": "",
  "Extinction of the original species": "",
  "Allopatric speciation through geographic isolation": "",
  "Gradual divergence due to natural selection": "",
  "This is sympatric speciation through autopolyploidy. The tetraploid cannot produce fertile offspring with the diploid parent species because crosses produce triploid offspring with unbalanced chromosome sets. A new species was instantly created without geographic isolation.": "",
  "Two species of frogs live in the same pond. Species A calls to mates in the evening, while Species B calls in the early morning. Even though they could physically interbreed, they never do. What type of reproductive barrier maintains their species identity?": "",
  "Hybrid sterility, a postzygotic barrier": "",
  "Temporal isolation, a prezygotic barrier based on different mating times": "",
  "Mechanical isolation due to incompatible body sizes": "",
  "Habitat isolation because they live in different ponds": "",
  "This is temporal isolation, a prezygotic barrier. The two species are active and calling at different times, so they never encounter potential mates from the other species. No geographic barrier is needed; timing alone prevents interbreeding.": "",
  "After the mass extinction event that killed the dinosaurs 66 million years ago, mammals rapidly diversified into many ecological roles previously occupied by dinosaurs. Within 10 million years, ancestral mammals had given rise to bats, whales, primates, and many other groups. What macroevolutionary pattern does this represent?": "",
  "Adaptive radiation following a mass extinction that opened ecological niches": "",
  "Convergent evolution of unrelated lineages": "",
  "Stabilizing selection maintaining mammalian body forms": "",
  "Genetic drift in small mammalian populations": "",
  "This is adaptive radiation: the rapid diversification of mammals into many new species occupying diverse ecological niches vacated by extinct dinosaurs. Mass extinctions often trigger adaptive radiations by removing dominant competitors and opening resources.": "",
  "Two closely related bird species occasionally mate and produce hybrid offspring that survive but are sterile. A scientist argues that these species are maintained as distinct biological species. What is the basis for this argument?": "",
  "The species must be in different geographic areas": "",
  "The hybrid offspring look different from both parent species": "",
  "The hybrids will eventually evolve to become fertile": "",
  "The postzygotic barrier of hybrid sterility prevents gene flow between the species, maintaining reproductive isolation": "",
  "Under the biological species concept, species are defined by reproductive isolation. Even though mating occurs, the sterile hybrids cannot pass on genes, so no gene flow occurs between species. Hybrid sterility is an effective postzygotic barrier maintaining species boundaries.": "",
  "A researcher examining the fossil record of a marine invertebrate finds that the species shows little morphological change for 3 million years, then rapidly develops new shell features over about 50,000 years before stabilizing again. Which model of evolutionary change does this pattern support?": "",
  "Punctuated equilibrium, with long stasis interrupted by rapid change": "",
  "The species was not evolving at any point during this time": "",
  "Constant directional selection throughout the entire period": "",
  "Gradualism, with slow and steady change": "",
  "This pattern of long stasis followed by rapid morphological change is the hallmark of punctuated equilibrium. The rapid change may correspond to a speciation event, while the long stable period represents the species in equilibrium with its environment.": "",
  "Apple maggot flies originally laid eggs on hawthorn fruits. When apple trees were introduced to North America, some flies began laying eggs on apples instead. These two populations now have different host preferences and breed at different times (apples fruit earlier). Genetic analysis shows the populations are diverging. What type of speciation may be in progress?": "",
  "Sympatric speciation through habitat differentiation and temporal isolation": "",
  "Speciation caused exclusively by genetic drift": "",
  "Allopatric speciation due to a mountain range separating the populations": "",
  "Artificial selection by farmers": "",
  "Apple maggot flies are a textbook example of sympatric speciation in progress. The two populations live in the same area but are reproductively isolated by host preference (habitat isolation) and different fruiting times (temporal isolation), leading to genetic divergence.": "",
  "Eastern and western meadowlarks look nearly identical and have overlapping ranges, but they have different songs and rarely interbreed. What type of prezygotic barrier maintains their species identity?": "",
  "Geographic isolation since they live in different areas": "",
  "Behavioral isolation through species-specific courtship songs": "",
  "Hybrid breakdown in later generations": "",
  "Gametic isolation preventing fertilization": "",
  "This is behavioral isolation (also called ethological isolation). Despite living in the same areas and looking similar, these species recognize mates through species-specific songs. Females only respond to the correct song, preventing interbreeding.": "",
  "Cichlid fish in Lake Victoria, Africa, have diversified into over 500 species in less than 15,000 years. Species differ in jaw shape, diet, coloration, and habitat use. What combination of evolutionary mechanisms best explains this extraordinary diversification?": "",
  "Adaptive radiation driven by natural and sexual selection exploiting diverse ecological niches in the lake": "",
  "Gene flow between all 500 species maintaining diversity": "",
  "Artificial selection by local fishermen": "",
  "Only genetic drift operating on isolated island populations": "",
  "Lake Victoria cichlids represent one of the fastest known adaptive radiations. Natural selection drove adaptation to different food sources and habitats, while sexual selection based on coloration promoted reproductive isolation, together producing remarkable species diversity.": "",
  "A wheat farmer discovers a plant in the field that is larger and has twice the normal number of chromosomes. This plant can produce seeds when self-pollinated but cannot cross with normal wheat plants. The farmer breeds this plant and creates a new variety. What evolutionary process occurred in the field?": "",
  "Extinction of the original wheat variety": "",
  "Gradual divergence through many generations of natural selection": "",
  "Instantaneous sympatric speciation through autopolyploidy, creating a new species in one generation": "",
  "This is autopolyploidy, where chromosome doubling within a single species creates a new polyploid individual that is reproductively isolated from the diploid parent species. This is one of the few mechanisms that can produce a new species in a single generation, and it is common in plants.": ""
}